			<ns0:name>b...@google.com</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/105821748722532785568/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">my paranoia says we should require the 32-bytes of HLT -- for all architectures -- at the boundary between text and data, read-only or otherwise.  this means dynamic text region's end, if the dynamic text region is present.  for the NaCl x86-32 sandbox, that means the HLTs are the last 32 bytes in the code segment; for the x86-64 and arm, this would be the last 32-bytes of the last executable page.  it should not be a requirement that all code chunks end with a HLT.

we could change things so that the validator doesn't check for the HLTs, but the service runtime either always overwrites those 32 bytes after loading and before verification.  it won't matter in the current sandboxing schemes if we do it after verification or not, but may in the future if/when we switch to one of the newer sandboxing schemes.</ns0:content><ns0:updated>2010-06-10T00:21:39.000Z</ns0:updated><ns0:published>2010-06-10T00:21:39.000Z</ns0:published><ns2:updates /><ns0:title>Comment 1 by b...@google.com</ns0:title><ns0:link href="http://code.google.com/p/nativeclient/issues/detail?id=585#c1" rel="alternate" type="text/html" /><ns0:link href="https://code.google.com/feeds/issues/p/nativeclient/issues/585/comments/full/1" rel="self" type="application/atom+xml" /></ns0:entry>